article.headline: Seattle snaps six-game slide
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics had been waiting for an offensive breakout and a victory. They got both Saturday night against the NBA's worst defense. Brent Barry went 6-for-6 from 3-point range and scored a season-high 25 points with 10 assists to lead the SuperSonics to a 115-101 victory over the Orlando Magic. "It was great to knock down those shots tonight," said Barry, who recently returned after missing 20 games with a hand injury. "Hopefully it means that I'm healthy again and able to play at that level the rest of the season." Seattle snapped a six-game losing streak, overcoming 40 points from Tracy McGrady in his first game since scoring 62. Barry shot 9-for-10 overall, while Ray Allen scored 26 and made four 3-pointers and Vladimir Radmanovic had three 3s among his 21 points. The Sonics made 14 3-pointers and shot a season-high 56 percent. "We were sharp on offense," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "We started out hot and really shared the ball tonight. It's nice when we have that type of movement, share the ball and have a number of guys knocking down shots." Tyronn Lue had 19 points for Orlando. Back-to-back 3-pointers by Radmanovic and Allen and a three-point play by Radmanovic allowed Seattle to withstand a fourth-quarter rally and win for just the fourth time since the All-Star break. "We let them score too easily," Magic coach Johnny Davis said. "You have to have an awareness, an alertness not to hug up to your man. It's called team defense, not just stop your guy. We've got to do a much better job at it." In the fourth quarter, Seattle made four of its first five shots from the field, including a pair of 3-pointers, to take a 92-80 lead. "I don't think I've seen that many open looks in a while," Allen said. McGrady's 18-footer was Orlando's only field goal in the first 5:30 of the quarter as the deficit grew to 100-86 on a pair of free throws by Radmanovic with 6:40 left. DeShawn Stevenson finally ended the drought for Orlando with a baseline jumper. McGrady followed with five straight points to cut the deficit to 100-91 with 5:22 remaining, but Allen and Radmanovic led the 9-2 run that wrapped up the victory. "Our defense was really bad," McGrady said. "I had it rolling again in the second half and then we'd go back at the other end and those guys were just getting easy layups and backdoors. We had a lot of defensive lapses." Neither team was able to get control in the first half when the biggest lead was Seattle's 39-31 advantage in the middle of the second quarter. The Sonics went to the locker room with a 51-45 lead despite shooting 54 percent.

Game notes
The Sonics shot a season-high 56.1 percent, including 14-of-28 from 3-point territory. ... Magic F Drew Gooden returned after a three-game absence because of a staph infection on his right leg. He was 1-for-6 from the field and scored four points in 20 minutes. ... The Magic outrebounded the Sonics 35-33, the first time they've outrebounded an opponent in seven games.
